Q1.  How did you hear about the workshop?
Q2.  Overall how would you rate the workshop?
Q3.  Was the workshop taught at an appropriate level?
Q5.  Do you feel more confident in your knowledge of this topic after the workshop?

column2: Handling high dimensional data like RNA-seq etc.
column6: Introduction to command line for analyzing biological data would be very useful, analyzing spcific types of data (ex. RNA-seq, differential gene expression, etc.)
column7: Statistical tests and what's appropriate for what kinds of data sets - this migh be a "bring your own data" kind of session or send it in advance and instructor chooses good examples from the group. (Note: For non-"omics" type data analysis)
column12: Statistics, gene expressions, cut/run, ChIP-seq analysis
column14: SeRNA seq, ATAC seq, data analysis
column17: We need longer time course and it's better to add session to solve specific questions with our own data (may two more sessions with TA around)
column20: RNAseq of ChIPseq data analysis in R
column23: More data analysis type of stuff (functions, error bases) actual gene expression analysis examples ChIPseq

column1: Q7.  Please add any other comments or suggestions for additional scientific enrichment workshops
column17: Would be cool to add single cell RNAseq analysis course using R software
column18: Longer sessions with some more fundamentals of R like data structures, type, & usages
column21: Course be a little longer covering more basics on what are vectors, classes, functions, etc. and longer course C2 sessions is too little
column23: Starts slowly, very basic, but then when we get to complicated stuff - no time! Put simple stuff in bootcamp homework
